This directory contains all the scripts that regard the analysis and preprocessing of our dataset.

In the .py file "convert_raw_to_numeric", we convert the dataset entries into numerical (regarding the columns "username",
"movie" and "rating", or to datetime objects, regarding the last column "date"

In the file "remove_duplicates", we grab "duplicate ratings", ie ratings that came from the same user regarding
the same movie. We drop the duplicates, keeping only the last entry (rating).

At "encode_missing_ratings", we make sure that our initial dataset does not contain any zeros, hence the absence of a rating
(from a user for a movie) must be encoded by us

In the file "exploratory_analysis", we perform an early, premature analysis of our dataset, to see how basic filtering
will alter our dataset, in terms of  the number of training points (users), dimensionality, and sparsity of the final
matrix.

In the file "user_filter_dimensionality_testing", we dive deeper into the dimensionality issue, and check whether a meaningful
dimensionality reduction can be achieved by solely filtering out users based on the number of ratings they have left.
Due to the disappointing results of this analysis, we move on to

The file "threshold_analysis" performs various checks regarding both filtering conditions, ie minimum number of ratings
per user *and* number of movies (dimensions) to be kept in the final dataset, in order to see which filtering
conditions achieve a balance between 1) as minimum information loss as possible, and 2) a meaningful dimensionality
reduction (plus a slight increase in the density of the final matrix).

In "threshold_analysis2", we extend our threshold-based filtering based on users and movies, only this time, instead of
examining "top N movies", we search for "movies with at least m ratings". This ensures that, after an iterative
filtering scheme (movies -> users -> movies -> users), the final dataset will consist of movies and users that actually
contribute information to our analysis. After determining our final thresholds, we complete our data preprocessing

In "final_preprocessing.py" the filtering of the dataset is applied, and the data come to a form suitable for our analysis
later (matrix "users x movies", where "0" entries denote the absence of a rating "user i for movie j")

